Author: Gateway#3763
Content:
[dscrd-hush] <1112> When i installed HUSH i saw it was downloading from some servers in Texas and some OVH servers in Paris. 

In the future, if someone wanted to use HUSH to communicate, how trivial would it be for an authority to block HUSH messages from being transmitted. 

Is all that's needed is a connection to at least one miner? (in the full version when it's completed)

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> @1112 sounds like you want to use Tor

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> HUSH needs to talk to it's p2p peers, and those could be anywhere

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> @1112 you can use `-onlynet=onion` to force Hush to only use Tor, or you can use something like TAILS that forces all connections to be Tor

Content: [dscrd-hush] <passcombo.com 🏴☠🍋> I have a question regarding t->t and t->z memo sending - is the memo for t-t tx visible publicly (no encyrption) ? encryption is working only on z-z ? and regrding z-z encryption - how it is being decrypted? wallet does decryption using private key ?

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> there is no memos in recipients which are taddrs, such at t=>t but also z=>t and z=>(z,t) etc.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> and yes, wallet does decryption of memos to a given zaddr via the private key of the zaddr
